{"title_page": "Stefan Molyneux", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Canadian podcaster and YouTuber}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Stephen Molyneux}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name          = Stefan Molyneux\n| image         = Stefan Molyneux 2014-02-10.jpg\n| caption       = Stefan Molyneux in 2014\n| birth_name    = Stefan Basil Molyneux\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1966|9|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[Athlone]], [[Ireland]]\n| spouse = Christina Papadopoulos<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\" />\n| channel_name     = Stefbot\n| residence     = [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\">{{cite news |last=Ha |first=Tu Thanh |date=December 19, 2014 |title=Controversial podcaster listened in on therapist wife and clients: lawsuit |url=https://beta.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/controversial-podcaster-listened-in-on-therapist-wife-and-clients-lawsuit-alleges/article22158708/ |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| nationality   = Canadian \n| occupation    = {{cslist|[[Podcast|Podcaster]] |[[YouTube personality]]}}\n| education     = [[History]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[McGill University]], 1991; [[Master of Arts|M.A.]], [[University of Toronto]], 1993)\n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present \n| network         = Freedomain Radio\n| associated_acts = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lauren Southern]]\n}}\n| website       = {{URL|freedomainradio.com}}\n| silver_year     = 2015 \n| stats_update    = February 02, 2019\n| silver_button   = yes\n}}\n\n'''Stefan Basil Molyneux''' ({{IPAc-en|s|t|\u0259|\u02c8|f|\u00e6|n|_|\u02c8|m|\u0252|l|\u1d7b|nj|u\u02d0}}; born September 24, 1966) is a [[far-right]], [[white nationalist]]<ref name=\"NBC News\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-sparks-islamophobic-theories-social-media-n995091|title=Notre Dame Cathedral fire spurs Islamophobic conspiracy theories on social media|last=Collins|first=Ben|date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/Hiv6P|archive-date=April 16, 2019|publisher=[[NBC News]]}}</ref> Canadian [[podcast]]er and [[List of YouTubers|YouTuber]] who is known for his promotion of [[scientific racism]] and [[white supremacist]] views.<ref name=\"splc\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/stefan-molyneux|title=Stefan Molyneux|publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324213909/https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/stefan-molyneux|archive-date=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/youtube-breaking-news.php|title=How YouTube reactionaries are breaking the news media|last=Beery|first=Zo\u00eb|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|publisher=[[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215133250/https://www.cjr.org/analysis/youtube-breaking-news.php|archive-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|title=Alternative Influence|last=Lewis|first=Rebecca|date=2018-09-18|access-date=2018-09-19|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918202818/https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|archive-date=2018-09-18|publisher=Data & Society Research Institute|page=37|language=en-US|quote=In his YouTube videos, Molyneux openly promotes scientific racism, advocates for the men's rights movement, critiques initiatives devoted to gender equity, and promotes white supremacist conspiracy theories focused on 'White Genocide' and 'The Great Replacement.'}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianRevival\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/02/the-unwelcome-revival-of-race-science|title=The unwelcome revival of 'race science'|last=Evans|first=Gavin|date=March 2, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220023319/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/02/the-unwelcome-revival-of-race-science|archive-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Online Othering|last=Winter|first=Aaron|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2019|isbn=978-3030126322|editor-last=Lumsden|editor-first=Karen|series=Palgrave Studies in Cybercrime and Cybersecurity|pages=39\u201363|language=en|chapter=Online Hate: From the Far-Right to the 'Alt-Right' and from the Margins to the Mainstream|doi=10.1007/978-3-030-12633-9_2|lccn=2019930706|editor2-last=Harmer|editor2-first=Emily}}</ref> \n\nMolyneux is described as a leading figure of the [[alt-right]] movement by ''[[Politico]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]'', and as a [[far-right]] activist.<ref name=\"Politico17\">{{cite news |last=Schreckinger |first=Ben |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Trump's Troll Army Isn't Ready for War in Syria |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/04/trump-alt-right-syria-war-214998 |newspaper=[[Politico|Politico Magazine]] |access-date=August 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810143416/http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/04/trump-alt-right-syria-war-214998 |archive-date=2017-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Washp17\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/03/10/canadas-obsession-with-american-politics-is-nothing-to-apologize-for/|title=Canada's obsession with American politics is nothing to apologize for|last=McCullough|first=J. J.|date=March 10, 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816022122/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/03/10/canadas-obsession-with-american-politics-is-nothing-to-apologize-for/|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/kfile-steve-king-molyneux-podcast/index.html|title=Rep. Steve King appeared on podcast frequented by white nationalists|last=McDermott|first=Nathan|date=November 30, 2018|access-date=2018-12-02|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202052135/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/kfile-steve-king-molyneux-podcast/index.html|archive-date=2018-12-02|publisher=[[CNN]]|last2=Kaczynski|first2=Andrew|last3=Massie|first3=Chris}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/08/technology/youtube-radical.html|title=The Making of a YouTube Radical|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2019-06-08|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-06-08|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/yV88p|archive-date=2019-06-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Tom Clements in ''[[The Independent]]'' described Molyneux as having \"a perverse fixation on race and IQ\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/alt-right-white-nationalist-richard-spencer-jonathan-bowden-nick-griffin-bnp-a9091376.html|title=I fell down the rabbit hole of alt-right propaganda and this is what I learned|last=Clements|first=Tom|date=4 September 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924155158/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/alt-right-white-nationalist-richard-spencer-jonathan-bowden-nick-griffin-bnp-a9091376.html|archive-date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Freedomain''' internet community which Molyneux leads has been described as a [[cult]], and Molyneux has been described as a cult leader, using [[indoctrination|cult indoctrination]] techniques on his followers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"Times-2009\"/><ref name=\"Globe-2008\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Background ==\nMolyneux was born in Ireland and raised mainly in [[London]] before moving to Canada at the age of 11.<ref name=Mississauga-2003 /> He attended [[Glendon College]] at [[York University]], where he was an actor at Theatre Glendon<ref name=Star-23Feb1988 /> and a member of the Debating Society.<ref name=ProTem-8Feb1988 /> He then attended the [[National Theatre School of Canada]] in Montreal.<ref name=Mississauga-2003 /><ref name=Burg-Star /> In 1991, at age 25, Molyneux received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree in History from [[McGill University]]. He received an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degree in History from the [[University of Toronto]] in 1993.<ref name=Globe-2008 /><ref name=Burg-Star />\n\n== Career ==\nIn early 1995, Molyneux and his brother Hugh founded Caribou Systems Corporation, a Toronto-based provider of environmental database software. The company was sold in 2000.<ref name=\"Burg-Star\" /><ref name=\"2002-01-28_Blue292\" />\n\nIn 2005, Molyneux began writing articles for libertarian website ''[[LewRockwell.com]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/author/stefan-molyneux/ |title=Articles by Stefan Molyneux |website=LewRockwell.com |access-date=25 November 2019}}</ref> before starting a podcast called ''Freedomain Radio'' (FDR).<ref name=\"freedomainradio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fdrpodcasts.com/#/0 |title=An Introduction to Freedomain Radio |website=Freedomainradio.com |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619035740/https://www.fdrpodcasts.com/#/0#/0 |archive-date=2018-06-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux funds his efforts through listener support.<ref name=\"Horsager-TheTrustEdge\">{{cite book |last=Horsager |first=David |date=October 2012 |title=The Trust Edge: How top leaders gain faster results, deeper relationships, and a stronger bottom line |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |location=New York |pages=25\u201326 |oclc=820783989 |isbn=978-1-4767-1137-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Molyneux interviewed James Damore, the [[Google]] employee who was fired after writing the [[Google's Ideological Echo Chamber]] memo.<ref name=\"Goo\">{{cite news |last=Levin |first=Sam |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Fired Google memo writer gives first big interviews to rightwing YouTubers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/09/james-damore-google-memo-youtube-interviews |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826052737/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/09/james-damore-google-memo-youtube-interviews |archive-date=2017-08-26 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Molyneux and Canadian internet personality [[Lauren Southern]] toured the Australian cities of [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kinsella |first1=Luke |title=What I learnt about the far right from Lauren Southern |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/what-i-learnt-about-the-far-right-from-lauren-southern/news-story/0443ce7a7a09dc8431776f469b34ae0d |accessdate=31 July 2018 |publisher=[[News.com.au]] |date=31 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731062217/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/what-i-learnt-about-the-far-right-from-lauren-southern/news-story/0443ce7a7a09dc8431776f469b34ae0d |archive-date=2018-07-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NITV]] quotes Simon Copland, an SBS freelance writer, who thinks that Molyneux disparaged pre-colonisation [[Indigenous Australians|Australian Aboriginal]] culture, calling it \"very violent\", and downplayed massacres perpetrated against Aborigines, saying that the European takeover of Australia had been less violent than other such takeovers, and that the settlers \"were trying to stop infanticide and mass rape\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Douglas |title=Far-right Canadian duo's vile rampage against Aboriginal culture at Sydney event |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/2017/07/30/far-right-canadian-duos-vile-rampage-against-aboriginal-culture-sydney-event |accessdate=31 July 2018 |publisher=[[National Indigenous Television]], [[Special Broadcasting Service]] |date=30 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730230015/https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/2017/07/30/far-right-canadian-duos-vile-rampage-against-aboriginal-culture-sydney-event |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux and Southern subsequently traveled to New Zealand for their speaking engagement at [[Auckland]]'s Powerstation theatre. The event was cancelled at the last minute when the Powerstation's owner rescinded the booking, citing opposition from local groups and the offensive content of their speech.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lauren Southern and Stefan Molyneux's speaking event cancelled |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2018/08/lauren-southern-and-stefan-molyneux-s-secret-speaking-location-revealed-as-the-powerstation.html |accessdate=3 August 2018 |publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=3 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803091516/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2018/08/lauren-southern-and-stefan-molyneux-s-secret-speaking-location-revealed-as-the-powerstation.html |archive-date=2018-08-03 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/106002242/aucklands-powerstation-owner-apologises-for-booking-controversial-speakers|title=Auckland's Powerstation owner apologises for booking controversial speakers|last1=Truebridge|first1=Nick|date=3 August 2018|work=|accessdate=3 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720091533/https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/106002242/aucklands-powerstation-owner-apologises-for-booking-controversial-speakers|archive-date=20 July 2019|publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|last2=Niall|first2=Todd}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/auckland-venue-cancels-controversial-far-right-canadian-pairs-speaking-event|title=Auckland venue cancels controversial far-right Canadian pair's speaking event|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=3 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114203849/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/auckland-venue-cancels-controversial-far-right-canadian-pairs-speaking-event|archive-date=14 January 2019|publisher=[[1 News]]}}</ref>\n\nMolyneux has frequently hosted prominent [[white supremacist]]s on his podcast, such as [[Peter Brimelow]] (founder of the white-nationalist website [[VDARE]]) and [[Jared Taylor]] (founder of the white-supremacist magazine ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'').<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn November 2019, [[PayPal]] suspended Molyneux's account. He had previously received donations via the service. PayPal's actions came after activist group [[Sleeping Giants]] had called for him to be removed, citing Molyneux's promotion of anti-Semitic conspiracy theories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gurley |first1=Lauren Kaori |title=PayPal Bans YouTuber Who Thinks Non-White People Are a Separate Species |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/pa74v9/paypal-bans-racist-youtuber-who-says-non-white-people-are-a-separate-species |accessdate=November 7, 2019 |work=Vice |date=November 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crowley |first1=James |title=PayPal to cut off donations to right-wing YouTuber Stefan Molyneux following social media divestment campaign |url=https://www.newsweek.com/alt-right-youtuber-cut-off-paypal-donations-1469936 |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |work=Newsweek |date=November 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In January 2020, Molyneux released a video in which he asked his followers for money and complained that he wouldn't be able to find regular employment after saying provocative things online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2020/01/stefan-molyneux-mocked-over-desperate-plea-that-he-ll-struggle-to-find-a-job.html|title=Stefan Molyneux mocked over desperate plea that he'll struggle to find a job|website=Newshub|date=14 January 2020|author=Daniel Rutledge\n}}</ref> Later that month, email marketing platform [[Mailchimp]] suspended Molyneux's account, which he used to send out his newsletter.<ref name=\"newsletter\">{{cite web|title=A prominent far-right commentator has been banned from sending his own newsletter|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/stefan-molyneux-newsletter-mailchimp-ban-far-right-9284346|website=Indy100|date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Climate change denial|climate change denier]] [[Naomi Seibt]] said Molyneux's YouTube material was one of her inspirations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirchgaessner |first1=Stephanie |title=Naomi Seibt: 'anti-Greta' activist called white nationalist an inspiration |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/feb/28/naomi-seibt-anti-greta-activist-white-nationalist-inspiration |website=The Guardian |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Anthony L. |title='The Anti-Greta' climate activist Naomi Seibt says she's 'absolutely' a fan of far-right podcaster Stefan Molyneux |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anti-greta-climate-activist-naomi-seibt-fan-stefan-molyneux-cpac-2020-2 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n=== Alt-right, racism and white supremacy ===\n\nMolyneux is known for his promotion of white supremacist views and for his promotion of related conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"GuardianRevival\"/><ref name=\"NBC News\"/><ref name=\"DandS\"/> He is a proponent of the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hankes |first1=Keegan |last2=Janik |first2=Rachel |last3=Hayden |first3=Michael Edison |title=Shooting at Poway Synagogue underscores link between internet radicalization and violence |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/04/28/shooting-poway-synagogue-underscores-link-between-internet-radicalization-and-violence |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=Southern Poverty Law Center |date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/362284/alt-right-speakers-stefan-molyneux-and-lauren-southern-anger-nz-muslims |title=Alt-right speakers Stefan Molyneux and Lauren Southern anger NZ Muslims |publisher=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=20 July 2018 |access-date=2018-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720114052/http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/362284/alt-right-speakers-stefan-molyneux-and-lauren-southern-anger-nz-muslims |archive-date=2018-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/02/us/politics/trump-twitter-disinformation.html|title=In Trump's Twitter Feed: Conspiracy-Mongers, Racists and Spies|last=McIntire|first=Mike|date=2019-11-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-02|last2=Yourish|first2=Karen|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Buchanan|first3=Larry}}</ref>\n\nMolyneux describes himself as an [[Anarcho-capitalism|anarcho-capitalist]].<ref name=\":3\" /> According to the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), Molyneux initially used the Freedomain Radio website \"to amplify his views on anarcho-capitalist ideology, atheism, philosophy, anti-statism, pseudo-therapy and anti-feminism.\" The SPLC also wrote that his views become more politically extreme and racialized around 2013 or 2014, when his ideology shifted to include far-right and [[ethno-nationalism|ethno-nationalist]] ideas.<ref name=\"splc\"/> Generally they describe him as an \"internet commentator and alleged cult leader who amplifies 'scientific racism', eugenics and white supremacism to a massive new audience\" and that \"Stefan Molyneux operates within the racist so-called 'alt-right' and pro-Trump ranks\".<ref name=\"splc\"/>\n\nMolyneux has been described as a part of the \"[[alt-right]]\" by ''[[Politico]]'', ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'', ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', and [[CBS News]], and has been described as \"one of the alt-right's biggest YouTube stars\" by ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' columnist J. J. McCullough.<ref name=\"Politico17\"/><ref name=\"Washp17\" /><ref name=Metro17>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Adam |date=August 19, 2017 |title=Heartbroken mother describes how she lost her son to alt-right movement |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/08/19/heartbroken-mother-pens-open-letter-to-son-she-lost-to-alt-right-movement-6864145/ |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |access-date=August 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819164720/http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/19/heartbroken-mother-pens-open-letter-to-son-she-lost-to-alt-right-movement-6864145/ |archive-date=2017-08-19 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kilgore |first=Ed |date=August 14, 2017 |title=Don't Look Now, But Alt-Right Demonstrations Are Scheduled for Nine Cities Next Weekend [Update: Now Cancelled] |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/08/alt-right-demonstrations-scheduled-for-9-cities-next-weekend.html |newspaper=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802193201/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/08/alt-right-demonstrations-scheduled-for-9-cities-next-weekend.html |archive-date=2018-08-02 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kosoff |first=Maya |date=August 9, 2017 |title=The Fired Google Engineer Is Doubling Down |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/08/james-damore-google-silicon-valley-culture-war |newspaper=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Fired Google Engineer Who Wrote Controversial Gender Essay Speaks Out |url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2017/08/09/google-gender-essay-fired-engineer-james-damore-legal-options/ |publisher=[[KPIX-TV]]/[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421090934/http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2017/08/09/google-gender-essay-fired-engineer-james-damore-legal-options/ |archive-date=2018-04-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Business Insider]]'', ''[[CNN]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', and ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' have characterized Molyneux as [[far-right]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Tani |first=Maxwell |date=August 23, 2017 |title='UNLIMITED WAR': Breitbart and the far right start to turn on Trump over his Afghanistan decision |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/far-right-trump-backers-pan-afghanistan-speech-2017-8 |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=August 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826075053/http://uk.businessinsider.com/far-right-trump-backers-pan-afghanistan-speech-2017-8 |archive-date=2017-08-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ling |first=Justin |date=January 8, 2018 |title=The Far Right Can't Decide If The Iran Protests Are A Good Thing, Or A George Soros Deep State Coup |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/justinling/the-far-right-cant-decide-if-the-iran-protests-are-a-good |publisher=[[BuzzFeed News]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612184725/https://www.buzzfeed.com/justinling/the-far-right-cant-decide-if-the-iran-protests-are-a-good |archive-date=2018-06-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> Data & Society, a research institute, described Molyneux as \"a Canadian talk show host who promotes [[scientific racism]]\".<ref name=\"DandS\">{{Cite news|url=https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|title=Alternative Influence|work=Data & Society|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918202818/https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|archive-date=2018-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', Molyneux is fixated with \"race realism\".  He has hosted white supremacists such as [[Jared Taylor]] on his show.  Molyneux has blamed \"rap culture\" for unarmed black men getting shot by police.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n[[Nassim Taleb]] argued that \"Molyneux thinks he can manage to keep ... catering to a [[Nordicism|Nordist supremacist]] following ... yet claim this is not racist so he doesn't get banned from social media\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=nntaleb |number=1079734921143431168 |date= 31 Dec 2018|title= Molyneux }}</ref>\n\n[[indy100]] describes Molyneux as a provocateur who \"has been allowed to promote a racist, transphobic, misogynistic and Islamophobic agenda on various platforms but has started to see his revenue diminish,\" while including a tweet by Molyneux in which he asserts that he is not a \"white nationalist\" in response to being banned from a popular platform.<ref name=\"newsletter\" />\n\n=== Men's rights activism ===\nMolyneux describes himself as a [[Men's rights movement|men's rights activist]].<ref name=\":3\" /> He was a panelist at a 2014 Detroit conference held by the [[men's rights movement]] and [[manosphere]] organization, [[A Voice for Men]]. According to Jessica Roy of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, Molyneux argued that violence in the world is the result of how women treat their children, and that: \"If we could just get people to be nice to their babies for five years straight, that would be it for war, drug abuse, addiction, promiscuity, sexually transmitted diseases, ... Almost all would be completely eliminated, because they all arise from dysfunctional early childhood experiences, which are all run by women\".<ref name=\"men\">{{cite news |last=Roy |first=Jessica |date=July 2, 2014 |title=What I Learned as a Woman at a Men's-Rights Conference |url=http://time.com/2949435/what-i-learned-as-a-woman-at-a-mens-rights-conference/ |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608215558/http://time.com/2949435/what-i-learned-as-a-woman-at-a-mens-rights-conference/ |archive-date=2018-06-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux believes feminism is a form of socialism.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Family-of-origin relationships ===\nMolyneux refers to the family that people are born into as their \"family-of-origin\", or \"FOO\". He suggests that family-of-origin relationships may not necessarily be desirable, and under given circumstances may even be detrimental, and thus, for those individuals unsatisfied with their childhood relationships, it would be advantageous for them to sever such involuntary relationships as adults, or \"deFOO\".<ref name=Guardian-2008>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/nov/15/family-relationships-fdr-defoo-cult |title=You will never see me again |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 7, 2009 |first=Kate |last=Hilpern |date=November 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131223212938/http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/nov/15/family-relationships-fdr-defoo-cult |archive-date=2013-12-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|Molyneux is quoted saying, \"Family relationships are voluntary and you should really work, if you're unhappy in these relationships, to improve the quality of those relationships \u2013 but to remember they do remain voluntary. And that gives people the motivation, I think, to try to improve them. But if you can't improve them \u2013 and we can't change other people, as we all know \u2013 for sure you should have the option to disengage.\"<ref name=\"Guardian-2008\" />}} In this way, he views all adult relationships as being voluntary and discretionary rather than obligatory. Molyneux has been quoted saying: \n{{quote|text=Deep down I do not believe that there are any really good parents out there \u2013 the same way that I do not believe there were any really good doctors in the 10th century.<ref name=\"Guardian-2008\" />}}\n\nA disciplinary panel at the [[College of Psychologists of Ontario]] spoke critically of \"deFOOing\" after a professional investigation into Molyneux's wife,<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\" /><ref name=\"tgamreprimand\">{{cite news |last=Rodan |first=Galit |date=November 1, 2012 |title=Therapist who told podcast listeners to shun their families reprimanded|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/therapist-who-told-podcast-listeners-to-shun-their-families-reprimanded/article4846791/ |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> saying that by the standards of the College, it \"may be appropriate to recommend family separation in cases of abuse\" only after a suitable evaluation of patient history to \"ascertain whether the advice [is] warranted in the circumstances\".<ref>{{citation |first1=Judy |last1=Cohen |first2=Mary |last2=Bradley |first3=Vincent |last3=Lacroix |first4=Milan |last4=Pomichalek |first5=Pamela Wilansky |last5=Traynor |title=IN THE MATTER OF The Regulated Health Professions Act, 1991, S.O. 1991, Chapter 18 and the Psychology Act, 1991, S.O. 1991, Chapter 38; AND IN THE MATTER OF Ms. Christina Papadopoulos, Psychological Associate; AND IN THE MATTER OF a hearing before a panel of the Discipline Committee of the College of Psychologists of Ontario concerning allegations of professional misconduct against Christina Papadopoulos, Psychological Associate as set out in the Amended Notice of Hearing dated May 17, 2012 |date=October 31, 2012 <!-- Note: The public register is dated differently to the hearing. --> |publisher=College of Psychologists of Ontario |url=https://members.cpo.on.ca/public_register/investigation_detail/124}}</ref> According to a 2008 article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', both Molyneux and his wife have dissociated from their families of origin.<ref name=Guardian-2008 />\n\n==Cult accusations==\n\nAccording to [[Steven Hassan]], a mental health counselor with experience on cults, \"Partly what's going on with the people on the Internet who are indoctrinated, they spend lots of hours on the computer. Videos can have them up all night for several nights in a row. Molyneux knows how to talk like he knows what he's talking about, despite very little academic research. He cites this and cites that, and presents it as the whole truth. It dismantles people's sense of self and replaces it with his sense of confidence about how to fix the world\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/meet-the-cult-leader-stumping-for-donald-trump|title=Meet the 'Cult' Leader Stumping for Donald Trump|last1=Collins|first1=Ben|date=5 February 2016|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=19 June 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012231804/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/05/meet-the-cult-leader-stumping-for-donald-trump.html|archivedate=2016-10-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Tu Thanh Ha wrote that Molyneux was called the leader of a \"therapy cult\" after Tom Bell, a Freedomain Radio community member, severed contact with his family.<ref name=\"Globe-2008\" /> In April 2008, Bell had called in to the show asking about his [[veganism]] and his feeling of disgust towards people who eat meat.<ref name=\"Times-2009\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-mother-and-son-torn-apart-by-web-cult-that-destroys-families-w8klkzndf50|title=The mother and son torn apart by web 'cult' that destroys families|last=Whipple|first=Tom|date=January 10, 2009|newspaper=[[The Times]]|accessdate=October 19, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Molyneux suggested that this disgust could have come from witnessing an authority figure who was cruel to animals.<ref name=\"Times-2009\" /> Bell responded by describing memories of his father being verbally and physically cruel to the family cat, causing him to feel intimidated by the father, and then described his [[emotional detachment]] toward his mother and the rest of his family.<ref name=\"Times-2009\" />\n\nThe following month, Bell left a note stating he no longer wanted contact and left home. It was reported that, of the estimated 50,000 users of the website, about 20 (0.04%) FDR members had also disassociated from their families-of-origin, and that many parents chose not to speak to the media in an effort to avoid alienating their children further.<ref name=Times-2009 /> A representative of the British [[Cult Information Centre]] said they were following FDR, and noted that one sign of cults was that they cut people off from their families. Molyneux responded by saying, \"If I advised a wife to leave an abusive husband, there would not be articles about how I am a cult leader\".<ref name=\"Times-2009\" />\n\nMolyneux and \"deFOOing\" were subjects of an investigative documentary by [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in the [[United Kingdom]], which aired on August 20, 2015.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel5.com/show/trapped-in-a-cult/|title=Trapped In A Cult?|date=2015-08-20|publisher=[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119211815/http://www.channel5.com/shows/trapped-in-a-cult|archive-date=2015-11-19|accessdate=2015-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wyatt |first=Daisy |date=August 20, 2015 |title=Trapped in a Cult? \u2013 TV review: Disappointing Channel 5 shock-doc fails to come up to scratch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/trapped-in-a-cult-tv-review-disappointing-channel-5-shock-doc-fails-to-come-up-to-scratch-10464473.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=November 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118201100/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/trapped-in-a-cult-tv-review-disappointing-channel-5-shock-doc-fails-to-come-up-to-scratch-10464473.html |archive-date=2015-11-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same subjects were also featured on the February 18, 2016 episode of the documentary series ''[[Dark Net (TV series)|Dark Net]]''. The episode calls ''Freedomain Radio'' a cult.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sho.com/dark-net/season/1/episode/5/trapped |title= Dark Net \u2013 Season 1, Episode 5 |website= Showtime |accessdate= 12 June 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170808093351/http://www.sho.com/dark-net/season/1/episode/5/trapped |archive-date= 2017-08-08 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"2002-01-28_Blue292\">{{cite press release |title=Blue292 acquires Caribou Systems |url=http://www.blue292.com/pub/newsandevents/companyannouncements.aspx?a=view&id=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030802025924/http://www.blue292.com/pub/newsandevents/companyannouncements.aspx?a=view&id=1 |archivedate= August 2, 2003 |publisher=Blue292 |place=Durham, NC |date=January 28, 2002 |accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Burg-Star>{{cite news |last=Burg |first=Robert |title=Their software keeps tabs on site data |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10BBE23015C8E780/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]], The |location=Ontario, Canada |page=Business: D1 |date=May 26, 1997 |via=[[NewsBank]] (Access World News) |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043913/http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10BBE23015C8E780/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |archive-date=2018-09-28 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Globe-2008>{{cite news |last=Ha |first=Tu Thanh |date=December 12, 2008 |title=How a cyberphilosopher convinced followers to cut off family |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/how-a-cyberphilosopher-convinced-followers-to-cut-off-family/article7511365/?page=all |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140511191619/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/how-a-cyberphilosopher-convinced-followers-to-cut-off-family/article7511365/?page=all |archive-date=2014-05-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Mississauga-2003>{{cite news |title=Author Stefan Molyneux To Russia, with love |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10E4169AE30BF068/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |newspaper=[[The Mississauga News]] |location=[[Mississauga]], Ontario |date=June 1, 2003 |page=Arts & Entertainment: 15 |via=[[NewsBank]] (Access World News) |issn=0834-6585 |oclc=290997481 |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |quote=Molyneux is an Irish-born author who grew up in England and Africa before coming to Canada 25 years ago. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613014937/http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10E4169AE30BF068/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |archive-date=2018-06-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ProTem-8Feb1988>{{cite news|last=da Costa|first=Cathy |title=World Champions at Glendon |url=http://pi.library.yorku.ca/ojs/index.php/protem/article/download/15635/14559|format=PDF|work=Pro Tem|publisher=[[York University]]/[[Glendon College]] |date=February 8, 1988 |page=4|accessdate=May 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Star-23Feb1988>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Phil |title=Horrors! Dracula's at Glendon College |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10C28D2E2077D420/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]], The |location=Ontario, Canada |date=February 23, 1988 |page=Neighbors: N17 |via=[[NewsBank]] (Access World News) |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043930/http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10C28D2E2077D420/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |archive-date=2018-09-28 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Stefan Molyneux}}\n* {{Official website||Official site \u2013 Freedomain Radio}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molyneux, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Anglo-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian men podcasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian podcasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Canadian white nationalists]]\n[[Category:Racism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics in Canada]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Male critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Bitcoin]]\n[[Category:People from Athlone]]\n[[Category:Race and intelligence controversy]]\n[[Category:Scientific racism]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Canadian podcaster and YouTuber}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Stephen Molyneux}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name          = Stefan Molyneux\n| image         = Stefan Molyneux 2014-02-10.jpg\n| caption       = Stefan Molyneux in 2014\n| birth_name    = Stefan Basil Molyneux\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1966|9|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[Athlone]], [[Ireland]]\n| spouse = Christina Papadopoulos<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\" />\n| channel_name     = Stefbot\n| residence     = [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\">{{cite news |last=Ha |first=Tu Thanh |date=December 19, 2014 |title=Controversial podcaster listened in on therapist wife and clients: lawsuit |url=https://beta.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/controversial-podcaster-listened-in-on-therapist-wife-and-clients-lawsuit-alleges/article22158708/ |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| nationality   = Canadian \n| occupation    = {{cslist|[[Podcast|Podcaster]] |[[YouTube personality]]}}\n| education     = [[History]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[McGill University]], 1991; [[Master of Arts|M.A.]], [[University of Toronto]], 1993)\n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present \n| network         = Freedomain Radio\n| associated_acts = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lauren Southern]]\n}}\n| website       = {{URL|freedomainradio.com}}\n| silver_year     = 2015 \n| stats_update    = February 02, 2019\n| silver_button   = yes\n}}\n\n'''Stefan Basil Molyneux''' ({{IPAc-en|s|t|\u0259|\u02c8|f|\u00e6|n|_|\u02c8|m|\u0252|l|\u1d7b|nj|u\u02d0}}; born September 24, 1966) is a [[far-right]], [[white nationalist]]<ref name=\"NBC News\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-sparks-islamophobic-theories-social-media-n995091|title=Notre Dame Cathedral fire spurs Islamophobic conspiracy theories on social media|last=Collins|first=Ben|date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/Hiv6P|archive-date=April 16, 2019|publisher=[[NBC News]]}}</ref> Canadian [[podcast]]er and [[List of YouTubers|YouTuber]] who is known for his promotion of [[scientific racism]] and [[white supremacist]] views.<ref name=\"splc\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/stefan-molyneux|title=Stefan Molyneux|publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324213909/https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/stefan-molyneux|archive-date=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/youtube-breaking-news.php|title=How YouTube reactionaries are breaking the news media|last=Beery|first=Zo\u00eb|date=February 14, 2019|website=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|publisher=[[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215133250/https://www.cjr.org/analysis/youtube-breaking-news.php|archive-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|title=Alternative Influence|last=Lewis|first=Rebecca|date=2018-09-18|access-date=2018-09-19|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918202818/https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|archive-date=2018-09-18|publisher=Data & Society Research Institute|page=37|language=en-US|quote=In his YouTube videos, Molyneux openly promotes scientific racism, advocates for the men's rights movement, critiques initiatives devoted to gender equity, and promotes white supremacist conspiracy theories focused on 'White Genocide' and 'The Great Replacement.'}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianRevival\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/02/the-unwelcome-revival-of-race-science|title=The unwelcome revival of 'race science'|last=Evans|first=Gavin|date=March 2, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220023319/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/02/the-unwelcome-revival-of-race-science|archive-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Online Othering|last=Winter|first=Aaron|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2019|isbn=978-3030126322|editor-last=Lumsden|editor-first=Karen|series=Palgrave Studies in Cybercrime and Cybersecurity|pages=39\u201363|language=en|chapter=Online Hate: From the Far-Right to the 'Alt-Right' and from the Margins to the Mainstream|doi=10.1007/978-3-030-12633-9_2|lccn=2019930706|editor2-last=Harmer|editor2-first=Emily}}</ref> \n\nMolyneux is described as a leading figure of the [[alt-right]] movement by ''[[Politico]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]'', and as a [[far-right]] activist.<ref name=\"Politico17\">{{cite news |last=Schreckinger |first=Ben |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Trump's Troll Army Isn't Ready for War in Syria |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/04/trump-alt-right-syria-war-214998 |newspaper=[[Politico|Politico Magazine]] |access-date=August 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810143416/http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/04/trump-alt-right-syria-war-214998 |archive-date=2017-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Washp17\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/03/10/canadas-obsession-with-american-politics-is-nothing-to-apologize-for/|title=Canada's obsession with American politics is nothing to apologize for|last=McCullough|first=J. J.|date=March 10, 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816022122/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/03/10/canadas-obsession-with-american-politics-is-nothing-to-apologize-for/|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/kfile-steve-king-molyneux-podcast/index.html|title=Rep. Steve King appeared on podcast frequented by white nationalists|last=McDermott|first=Nathan|date=November 30, 2018|access-date=2018-12-02|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202052135/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/kfile-steve-king-molyneux-podcast/index.html|archive-date=2018-12-02|publisher=[[CNN]]|last2=Kaczynski|first2=Andrew|last3=Massie|first3=Chris}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/08/technology/youtube-radical.html|title=The Making of a YouTube Radical|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2019-06-08|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-06-08|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/yV88p|archive-date=2019-06-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref> Tom Clements in ''[[The Independent]]'' described Molyneux as having \"a perverse fixation on race and IQ\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/alt-right-white-nationalist-richard-spencer-jonathan-bowden-nick-griffin-bnp-a9091376.html|title=I fell down the rabbit hole of alt-right propaganda and this is what I learned|last=Clements|first=Tom|date=4 September 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924155158/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/alt-right-white-nationalist-richard-spencer-jonathan-bowden-nick-griffin-bnp-a9091376.html|archive-date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Freedomain''' internet community which Molyneux leads has been described as a [[cult]], and Molyneux has been described as a cult leader, using [[indoctrination|cult indoctrination]] techniques on his followers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"Times-2009\"/><ref name=\"Globe-2008\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Background ==\nMolyneux was born in Ireland and raised mainly in [[London]] before moving to Canada at the age of 11.<ref name=Mississauga-2003 /> He attended [[Glendon College]] at [[York University]], where he was an actor at Theatre Glendon<ref name=Star-23Feb1988 /> and a member of the Debating Society.<ref name=ProTem-8Feb1988 /> He then attended the [[National Theatre School of Canada]] in Montreal.<ref name=Mississauga-2003 /><ref name=Burg-Star /> In 1991, at age 25, Molyneux received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree in History from [[McGill University]]. He received an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degree in History from the [[University of Toronto]] in 1993.<ref name=Globe-2008 /><ref name=Burg-Star />\n\n== Career ==\nIn early 1995, Molyneux and his brother Hugh founded Caribou Systems Corporation, a Toronto-based provider of environmental database software. The company was sold in 2000.<ref name=\"Burg-Star\" /><ref name=\"2002-01-28_Blue292\" />\n\nIn 2005, Molyneux began writing articles for libertarian website ''[[LewRockwell.com]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/author/stefan-molyneux/ |title=Articles by Stefan Molyneux |website=LewRockwell.com |access-date=25 November 2019}}</ref> before starting a podcast called ''Freedomain Radio'' (FDR).<ref name=\"freedomainradio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fdrpodcasts.com/#/0 |title=An Introduction to Freedomain Radio |website=Freedomainradio.com |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619035740/https://www.fdrpodcasts.com/#/0#/0 |archive-date=2018-06-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux funds his efforts through listener support.<ref name=\"Horsager-TheTrustEdge\">{{cite book |last=Horsager |first=David |date=October 2012 |title=The Trust Edge: How top leaders gain faster results, deeper relationships, and a stronger bottom line |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |location=New York |pages=25\u201326 |oclc=820783989 |isbn=978-1-4767-1137-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Molyneux interviewed James Damore, the [[Google]] employee who was fired after writing the [[Google's Ideological Echo Chamber]] memo.<ref name=\"Goo\">{{cite news |last=Levin |first=Sam |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Fired Google memo writer gives first big interviews to rightwing YouTubers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/09/james-damore-google-memo-youtube-interviews |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826052737/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/09/james-damore-google-memo-youtube-interviews |archive-date=2017-08-26 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Molyneux and Canadian internet personality [[Lauren Southern]] toured the Australian cities of [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kinsella |first1=Luke |title=What I learnt about the far right from Lauren Southern |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/what-i-learnt-about-the-far-right-from-lauren-southern/news-story/0443ce7a7a09dc8431776f469b34ae0d |accessdate=31 July 2018 |publisher=[[News.com.au]] |date=31 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731062217/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/what-i-learnt-about-the-far-right-from-lauren-southern/news-story/0443ce7a7a09dc8431776f469b34ae0d |archive-date=2018-07-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NITV]] quotes Simon Copland, an SBS freelance writer, who thinks that Molyneux disparaged pre-colonisation [[Indigenous Australians|Australian Aboriginal]] culture, calling it \"very violent\", and downplayed massacres perpetrated against Aborigines, saying that the European takeover of Australia had been less violent than other such takeovers, and that the settlers \"were trying to stop infanticide and mass rape\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Douglas |title=Far-right Canadian duo's vile rampage against Aboriginal culture at Sydney event |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/2017/07/30/far-right-canadian-duos-vile-rampage-against-aboriginal-culture-sydney-event |accessdate=31 July 2018 |publisher=[[National Indigenous Television]], [[Special Broadcasting Service]] |date=30 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730230015/https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/2017/07/30/far-right-canadian-duos-vile-rampage-against-aboriginal-culture-sydney-event |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux and Southern subsequently traveled to New Zealand for their speaking engagement at [[Auckland]]'s Powerstation theatre. The event was cancelled at the last minute when the Powerstation's owner rescinded the booking, citing opposition from local groups and the offensive content of their speech.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lauren Southern and Stefan Molyneux's speaking event cancelled |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2018/08/lauren-southern-and-stefan-molyneux-s-secret-speaking-location-revealed-as-the-powerstation.html |accessdate=3 August 2018 |publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=3 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803091516/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2018/08/lauren-southern-and-stefan-molyneux-s-secret-speaking-location-revealed-as-the-powerstation.html |archive-date=2018-08-03 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/106002242/aucklands-powerstation-owner-apologises-for-booking-controversial-speakers|title=Auckland's Powerstation owner apologises for booking controversial speakers|last1=Truebridge|first1=Nick|date=3 August 2018|work=|accessdate=3 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720091533/https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/106002242/aucklands-powerstation-owner-apologises-for-booking-controversial-speakers|archive-date=20 July 2019|publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|last2=Niall|first2=Todd}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/auckland-venue-cancels-controversial-far-right-canadian-pairs-speaking-event|title=Auckland venue cancels controversial far-right Canadian pair's speaking event|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=3 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114203849/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/auckland-venue-cancels-controversial-far-right-canadian-pairs-speaking-event|archive-date=14 January 2019|publisher=[[1 News]]}}</ref>\n\nMolyneux has frequently hosted prominent [[white supremacist]]s on his podcast, such as [[Peter Brimelow]] (founder of the white-nationalist website [[VDARE]]) and [[Jared Taylor]] (founder of the white-supremacist magazine ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'').<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn November 2019, [[PayPal]] suspended Molyneux's account. He had previously received donations via the service. PayPal's actions came after activist group [[Sleeping Giants]] had called for him to be removed, citing Molyneux's promotion of anti-Semitic conspiracy theories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gurley |first1=Lauren Kaori |title=PayPal Bans YouTuber Who Thinks Non-White People Are a Separate Species |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/pa74v9/paypal-bans-racist-youtuber-who-says-non-white-people-are-a-separate-species |accessdate=November 7, 2019 |work=Vice |date=November 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crowley |first1=James |title=PayPal to cut off donations to right-wing YouTuber Stefan Molyneux following social media divestment campaign |url=https://www.newsweek.com/alt-right-youtuber-cut-off-paypal-donations-1469936 |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |work=Newsweek |date=November 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In January 2020, Molyneux released a video in which he asked his followers for money and complained he won't be able to find regular employment after saying provocative things online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2020/01/stefan-molyneux-mocked-over-desperate-plea-that-he-ll-struggle-to-find-a-job.html|title=Stefan Molyneux mocked over desperate plea that he'll struggle to find a job|website=Newshub|date=14 January 2020|author=Daniel Rutledge\n}}</ref> Later that month, email marketing platform [[Mailchimp]] suspended Molyneux's account, which he used to send out his newsletter.<ref name=\"newsletter\">{{cite web|title=A prominent far-right commentator has been banned from sending his own newsletter|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/stefan-molyneux-newsletter-mailchimp-ban-far-right-9284346|website=Indy100|date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Climate change denial|climate change denier]] [[Naomi Seibt]] said Molyneux's YouTube material was one of her inspirations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirchgaessner |first1=Stephanie |title=Naomi Seibt: 'anti-Greta' activist called white nationalist an inspiration |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/feb/28/naomi-seibt-anti-greta-activist-white-nationalist-inspiration |website=The Guardian |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Anthony L. |title='The Anti-Greta' climate activist Naomi Seibt says she's 'absolutely' a fan of far-right podcaster Stefan Molyneux |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anti-greta-climate-activist-naomi-seibt-fan-stefan-molyneux-cpac-2020-2 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n=== Alt-right, racism and white supremacy ===\n\nMolyneux is known for his promotion of white supremacist views and for his promotion of related conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"GuardianRevival\"/><ref name=\"NBC News\"/><ref name=\"DandS\"/> He is a proponent of the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hankes |first1=Keegan |last2=Janik |first2=Rachel |last3=Hayden |first3=Michael Edison |title=Shooting at Poway Synagogue underscores link between internet radicalization and violence |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/04/28/shooting-poway-synagogue-underscores-link-between-internet-radicalization-and-violence |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=Southern Poverty Law Center |date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/362284/alt-right-speakers-stefan-molyneux-and-lauren-southern-anger-nz-muslims |title=Alt-right speakers Stefan Molyneux and Lauren Southern anger NZ Muslims |publisher=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=20 July 2018 |access-date=2018-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720114052/http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/362284/alt-right-speakers-stefan-molyneux-and-lauren-southern-anger-nz-muslims |archive-date=2018-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/02/us/politics/trump-twitter-disinformation.html|title=In Trump's Twitter Feed: Conspiracy-Mongers, Racists and Spies|last=McIntire|first=Mike|date=2019-11-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-02|last2=Yourish|first2=Karen|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Buchanan|first3=Larry}}</ref>\n\nMolyneux describes himself as an [[Anarcho-capitalism|anarcho-capitalist]].<ref name=\":3\" /> According to the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), Molyneux initially used the Freedomain Radio website \"to amplify his views on anarcho-capitalist ideology, atheism, philosophy, anti-statism, pseudo-therapy and anti-feminism.\" The SPLC also wrote that his views become more politically extreme and racialized around 2013 or 2014, when his ideology shifted to include far-right and [[ethno-nationalism|ethno-nationalist]] ideas.<ref name=\"splc\"/> Generally they describe him as an \"internet commentator and alleged cult leader who amplifies 'scientific racism', eugenics and white supremacism to a massive new audience\" and that \"Stefan Molyneux operates within the racist so-called 'alt-right' and pro-Trump ranks\".<ref name=\"splc\"/>\n\nMolyneux has been described as a part of the \"[[alt-right]]\" by ''[[Politico]]'', ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'', ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', and [[CBS News]], and has been described as \"one of the alt-right's biggest YouTube stars\" by ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' columnist J. J. McCullough.<ref name=\"Politico17\"/><ref name=\"Washp17\" /><ref name=Metro17>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Adam |date=August 19, 2017 |title=Heartbroken mother describes how she lost her son to alt-right movement |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/08/19/heartbroken-mother-pens-open-letter-to-son-she-lost-to-alt-right-movement-6864145/ |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |access-date=August 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819164720/http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/19/heartbroken-mother-pens-open-letter-to-son-she-lost-to-alt-right-movement-6864145/ |archive-date=2017-08-19 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kilgore |first=Ed |date=August 14, 2017 |title=Don't Look Now, But Alt-Right Demonstrations Are Scheduled for Nine Cities Next Weekend [Update: Now Cancelled] |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/08/alt-right-demonstrations-scheduled-for-9-cities-next-weekend.html |newspaper=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802193201/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/08/alt-right-demonstrations-scheduled-for-9-cities-next-weekend.html |archive-date=2018-08-02 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kosoff |first=Maya |date=August 9, 2017 |title=The Fired Google Engineer Is Doubling Down |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/08/james-damore-google-silicon-valley-culture-war |newspaper=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Fired Google Engineer Who Wrote Controversial Gender Essay Speaks Out |url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2017/08/09/google-gender-essay-fired-engineer-james-damore-legal-options/ |publisher=[[KPIX-TV]]/[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421090934/http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2017/08/09/google-gender-essay-fired-engineer-james-damore-legal-options/ |archive-date=2018-04-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Business Insider]]'', ''[[CNN]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', and ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' have characterized Molyneux as [[far-right]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Tani |first=Maxwell |date=August 23, 2017 |title='UNLIMITED WAR': Breitbart and the far right start to turn on Trump over his Afghanistan decision |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/far-right-trump-backers-pan-afghanistan-speech-2017-8 |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=August 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826075053/http://uk.businessinsider.com/far-right-trump-backers-pan-afghanistan-speech-2017-8 |archive-date=2017-08-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ling |first=Justin |date=January 8, 2018 |title=The Far Right Can't Decide If The Iran Protests Are A Good Thing, Or A George Soros Deep State Coup |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/justinling/the-far-right-cant-decide-if-the-iran-protests-are-a-good |publisher=[[BuzzFeed News]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612184725/https://www.buzzfeed.com/justinling/the-far-right-cant-decide-if-the-iran-protests-are-a-good |archive-date=2018-06-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> Data & Society, a research institute, described Molyneux as \"a Canadian talk show host who promotes [[scientific racism]]\".<ref name=\"DandS\">{{Cite news|url=https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|title=Alternative Influence|work=Data & Society|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918202818/https://datasociety.net/output/alternative-influence/|archive-date=2018-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', Molyneux is fixated with \"race realism\".  He has hosted white supremacists such as [[Jared Taylor]] on his show.  Molyneux has blamed \"rap culture\" for unarmed black men getting shot by police.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n[[Nassim Taleb]] argued that \"Molyneux thinks he can manage to keep ... catering to a [[Nordicism|Nordist supremacist]] following ... yet claim this is not racist so he doesn't get banned from social media\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=nntaleb |number=1079734921143431168 |date= 31 Dec 2018|title= Molyneux }}</ref>\n\n[[indy100]] describes Molyneux as a provocateur who \"has been allowed to promote a racist, transphobic, misogynistic and Islamophobic agenda on various platforms but has started to see his revenue diminish,\" while including a tweet by Molyneux in which he asserts that he is not a \"white nationalist\" in response to being banned from a popular platform.<ref name=\"newsletter\" />\n\n=== Men's rights activism ===\nMolyneux describes himself as a [[Men's rights movement|men's rights activist]].<ref name=\":3\" /> He was a panelist at a 2014 Detroit conference held by the [[men's rights movement]] and [[manosphere]] organization, [[A Voice for Men]]. According to Jessica Roy of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, Molyneux argued that violence in the world is the result of how women treat their children, and that: \"If we could just get people to be nice to their babies for five years straight, that would be it for war, drug abuse, addiction, promiscuity, sexually transmitted diseases, ... Almost all would be completely eliminated, because they all arise from dysfunctional early childhood experiences, which are all run by women\".<ref name=\"men\">{{cite news |last=Roy |first=Jessica |date=July 2, 2014 |title=What I Learned as a Woman at a Men's-Rights Conference |url=http://time.com/2949435/what-i-learned-as-a-woman-at-a-mens-rights-conference/ |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=May 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608215558/http://time.com/2949435/what-i-learned-as-a-woman-at-a-mens-rights-conference/ |archive-date=2018-06-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> Molyneux believes feminism is a form of socialism.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Family-of-origin relationships ===\nMolyneux refers to the family that people are born into as their \"family-of-origin\", or \"FOO\". He suggests that family-of-origin relationships may not necessarily be desirable, and under given circumstances may even be detrimental, and thus, for those individuals unsatisfied with their childhood relationships, it would be advantageous for them to sever such involuntary relationships as adults, or \"deFOO\".<ref name=Guardian-2008>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/nov/15/family-relationships-fdr-defoo-cult |title=You will never see me again |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 7, 2009 |first=Kate |last=Hilpern |date=November 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131223212938/http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/nov/15/family-relationships-fdr-defoo-cult |archive-date=2013-12-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|Molyneux is quoted saying, \"Family relationships are voluntary and you should really work, if you're unhappy in these relationships, to improve the quality of those relationships \u2013 but to remember they do remain voluntary. And that gives people the motivation, I think, to try to improve them. But if you can't improve them \u2013 and we can't change other people, as we all know \u2013 for sure you should have the option to disengage.\"<ref name=\"Guardian-2008\" />}} In this way, he views all adult relationships as being voluntary and discretionary rather than obligatory. Molyneux has been quoted saying: \n{{quote|text=Deep down I do not believe that there are any really good parents out there \u2013 the same way that I do not believe there were any really good doctors in the 10th century.<ref name=\"Guardian-2008\" />}}\n\nA disciplinary panel at the [[College of Psychologists of Ontario]] spoke critically of \"deFOOing\" after a professional investigation into Molyneux's wife,<ref name=\"tgamlawsuit\" /><ref name=\"tgamreprimand\">{{cite news |last=Rodan |first=Galit |date=November 1, 2012 |title=Therapist who told podcast listeners to shun their families reprimanded|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/therapist-who-told-podcast-listeners-to-shun-their-families-reprimanded/article4846791/ |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> saying that by the standards of the College, it \"may be appropriate to recommend family separation in cases of abuse\" only after a suitable evaluation of patient history to \"ascertain whether the advice [is] warranted in the circumstances\".<ref>{{citation |first1=Judy |last1=Cohen |first2=Mary |last2=Bradley |first3=Vincent |last3=Lacroix |first4=Milan |last4=Pomichalek |first5=Pamela Wilansky |last5=Traynor |title=IN THE MATTER OF The Regulated Health Professions Act, 1991, S.O. 1991, Chapter 18 and the Psychology Act, 1991, S.O. 1991, Chapter 38; AND IN THE MATTER OF Ms. Christina Papadopoulos, Psychological Associate; AND IN THE MATTER OF a hearing before a panel of the Discipline Committee of the College of Psychologists of Ontario concerning allegations of professional misconduct against Christina Papadopoulos, Psychological Associate as set out in the Amended Notice of Hearing dated May 17, 2012 |date=October 31, 2012 <!-- Note: The public register is dated differently to the hearing. --> |publisher=College of Psychologists of Ontario |url=https://members.cpo.on.ca/public_register/investigation_detail/124}}</ref> According to a 2008 article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', both Molyneux and his wife have dissociated from their families of origin.<ref name=Guardian-2008 />\n\n==Cult accusations==\n\nAccording to [[Steven Hassan]], a mental health counselor with experience on cults, \"Partly what's going on with the people on the Internet who are indoctrinated, they spend lots of hours on the computer. Videos can have them up all night for several nights in a row. Molyneux knows how to talk like he knows what he's talking about, despite very little academic research. He cites this and cites that, and presents it as the whole truth. It dismantles people's sense of self and replaces it with his sense of confidence about how to fix the world\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/meet-the-cult-leader-stumping-for-donald-trump|title=Meet the 'Cult' Leader Stumping for Donald Trump|last1=Collins|first1=Ben|date=5 February 2016|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=19 June 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012231804/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/05/meet-the-cult-leader-stumping-for-donald-trump.html|archivedate=2016-10-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Tu Thanh Ha wrote that Molyneux was called the leader of a \"therapy cult\" after Tom Bell, a Freedomain Radio community member, severed contact with his family.<ref name=\"Globe-2008\" /> In April 2008, Bell had called in to the show asking about his [[veganism]] and his feeling of disgust towards people who eat meat.<ref name=\"Times-2009\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-mother-and-son-torn-apart-by-web-cult-that-destroys-families-w8klkzndf50|title=The mother and son torn apart by web 'cult' that destroys families|last=Whipple|first=Tom|date=January 10, 2009|newspaper=[[The Times]]|accessdate=October 19, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Molyneux suggested that this disgust could have come from witnessing an authority figure who was cruel to animals.<ref name=\"Times-2009\" /> Bell responded by describing memories of his father being verbally and physically cruel to the family cat, causing him to feel intimidated by the father, and then described his [[emotional detachment]] toward his mother and the rest of his family.<ref name=\"Times-2009\" />\n\nThe following month, Bell left a note stating he no longer wanted contact and left home. It was reported that, of the estimated 50,000 users of the website, about 20 (0.04%) FDR members had also disassociated from their families-of-origin, and that many parents chose not to speak to the media in an effort to avoid alienating their children further.<ref name=Times-2009 /> A representative of the British [[Cult Information Centre]] said they were following FDR, and noted that one sign of cults was that they cut people off from their families. Molyneux responded by saying, \"If I advised a wife to leave an abusive husband, there would not be articles about how I am a cult leader\".<ref name=\"Times-2009\" />\n\nMolyneux and \"deFOOing\" were subjects of an investigative documentary by [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in the [[United Kingdom]], which aired on August 20, 2015.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channel5.com/show/trapped-in-a-cult/|title=Trapped In A Cult?|date=2015-08-20|publisher=[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119211815/http://www.channel5.com/shows/trapped-in-a-cult|archive-date=2015-11-19|accessdate=2015-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wyatt |first=Daisy |date=August 20, 2015 |title=Trapped in a Cult? \u2013 TV review: Disappointing Channel 5 shock-doc fails to come up to scratch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/trapped-in-a-cult-tv-review-disappointing-channel-5-shock-doc-fails-to-come-up-to-scratch-10464473.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=November 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118201100/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/trapped-in-a-cult-tv-review-disappointing-channel-5-shock-doc-fails-to-come-up-to-scratch-10464473.html |archive-date=2015-11-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same subjects were also featured on the February 18, 2016 episode of the documentary series ''[[Dark Net (TV series)|Dark Net]]''. The episode calls ''Freedomain Radio'' a cult.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sho.com/dark-net/season/1/episode/5/trapped |title= Dark Net \u2013 Season 1, Episode 5 |website= Showtime |accessdate= 12 June 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170808093351/http://www.sho.com/dark-net/season/1/episode/5/trapped |archive-date= 2017-08-08 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"2002-01-28_Blue292\">{{cite press release |title=Blue292 acquires Caribou Systems |url=http://www.blue292.com/pub/newsandevents/companyannouncements.aspx?a=view&id=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030802025924/http://www.blue292.com/pub/newsandevents/companyannouncements.aspx?a=view&id=1 |archivedate= August 2, 2003 |publisher=Blue292 |place=Durham, NC |date=January 28, 2002 |accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Burg-Star>{{cite news |last=Burg |first=Robert |title=Their software keeps tabs on site data |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10BBE23015C8E780/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]], The |location=Ontario, Canada |page=Business: D1 |date=May 26, 1997 |via=[[NewsBank]] (Access World News) |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043913/http://docs.newsbank.com/s/InfoWeb/aggdocs/AWNB/10BBE23015C8E780/0EB2D3A803A21E8C?s_lang=en-US |archive-date=2018-09-28 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Globe-2008>{{cite news |last=Ha |first=Tu Thanh |date=December 12, 2008 |title=How a cyberphilosopher convinced followers to cut off family |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/how-a-cyberphilosopher-convinced-followers-to-cut-off-family/article7511365/?page=all |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access