013 Freedomain Radio}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molyneux, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Anglo-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian men podcasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian podcasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Canadian white nationalists]]\n[[Category:Racism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics in Canada]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Male critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Bitcoin]]\n[[Category:People from Athlone]]\n[[Category:Race and intelligence controversy]]\n[[Category:Scientific racism]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Isi96", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stefan_Molyneux"}
{"title_page": "The Suicide Squad (film)", "text_new": "{{For|the previous film from 2016|Suicide Squad (film)}}\n{{short description|2021 superhero film}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Suicide Squad\n| image          = File:The Suicide Squad - official film logo.png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Official logo\n| director       = [[James Gunn]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Roven]]\n* [[Peter Safran]]\n* Simon Hatt<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/12/31/the-suicide-squad-director-explains-why-its-the-most-fun-hes-had/|title='The Suicide Squad' Director Explains Why It's the Most Fun He's Had Making a Movie|last=Perry|first=Spencer|website=Comicbook.com|date=December 30, 2019|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Do not add De Luca and Lin; sources have not noted them since Gunn took over-->\n}}\n| writer         = James Gunn\n| story          = \n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Suicide Squad]]|[[John Ostrander]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Margot Robbie]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Viola Davis]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Jai Courtney]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[David Dastmalchian]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Daniela Melchior]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n* [[Steve Agee]]\n<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Henry Braham]]\n| editing        = [[Fred Raskin]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DC Films]]\n* [[Atlas Entertainment]]\n* [[The Safran Company]]\n* Troll Court Entertainment \n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2021|8|6|United States}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Suicide Squad''''',<!--DO NOT REMOVE! This was the official title for four years and is still used in reliable sources.--> also known as '''''Suicide Squad 2''''',<!--DO NOT REMOVE! This was the official title for four years and is still used in reliable sources.--> is an upcoming American [[superhero film]] based on the [[DC Comics]] [[antihero]] team [[Suicide Squad]]. Set for distribution by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], it is intended to be a [[reboot]] to ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'' (2016) and the tenth film in the [[DC Extended Universe]] (DCEU). The film, written and directed by [[James Gunn]], stars an [[ensemble cast]] featuring <!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->[[Margot Robbie]], [[Viola Davis]], [[Joel Kinnaman]], [[Jai Courtney]], [[David Dastmalchian]], [[Daniela Melchior]], and [[Steve Agee]].<!-- These are actors whose roles have been confirmed. Do not add more names until their roles have been as well.-->\n\nPlans for a sequel to ''Suicide Squad'' began before that film's release and were confirmed in March 2016. Though director [[David Ayer]] was initially set to return, he dropped out in December 2016 in favor of ''[[Gotham City Sirens#Film|Gotham City Sirens]]''. Warner Bros. considered multiple directors, including [[Mel Gibson]] and [[Daniel Espinosa]], before hiring [[Gavin O'Connor (filmmaker)|Gavin O'Connor]] in September 2017. However, O'Connor left the project a year later due to creative differences. In October 2018, [[James Gunn]], who at the time had been fired by [[The Walt Disney Company]] from directing the [[Marvel Studios]] film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3]]'', was hired to write the film, and signed on to direct in January 2019. Gunn looked to the 1980s ''Suicide Squad'' comics for inspiration and chose to focus on new characters rather than continue the 2016 film's narrative. [[Principal photography]] began in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] in September 2019, and concluded in February 2020.\n\n''The Suicide Squad'' is scheduled to be released in the United States on August 6, 2021.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Margot Robbie]] as [[Harley Quinn|Harleen Quinzel / Harley Quinn]]: A crazed criminal and former [[psychiatrist]].<ref name=\"ElbaRobbie\" />\n* [[Viola Davis]] as [[Amanda Waller]]: The government official who organized the Suicide Squad and gives out the team's orders.<ref name=\"Davis\" />\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]] as [[Rick Flag]]:<ref name=\"CenaReidJoinCast\"/> The leader of the Suicide Squad.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hough |first1=Q.V. |title=Joel Kinnaman Returning As Rick Flag in James Gunn's Suicide Squad |url=https://screenrant.com/suicide-squad-2-joel-kinnaman-rick-flag-returning/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |accessdate=July 23, 2019 |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jai Courtney]] as [[Captain Boomerang|George \"Digger\" Harkness / Captain Boomerang]]: An unhinged thief who uses boomerangs as weapons.<ref name=\"Courtney\" />\n* [[David Dastmalchian]] as [[Polka-Dot Man|Abner Krill / Polka-Dot Man]]<ref name=\"Dastmalchian\">{{cite news |last1=Couch |first1=Aaron |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-sequel-casts-david-dastmalchian-as-polka-dot-man-1205280 |title=James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad' Casts 'Ant-Man' Actor David Dastmalchian (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=April 29, 2019 |accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Daniela Melchior]] as [[Ratcatcher (comics)|Ratcatcher]]<ref name=\"Melchior cast\">{{cite web|last=Kroll|first=Justin|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/daniela-melchior-ratcatcher-suicide-squad-sequel-1203201879/|title=Newcomer Daniela Melchior Eyed for Ratcatcher Role in 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (Exclusive)|date=April 30, 2019|accessdate=June 1, 2019|work=Variety}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Agee]] as the voice of [[King Shark]]<ref name=\"Agee cast\">{{cite web |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Comedian Steve Agee Joining James Gunn\u2019s \u2018Suicide Squad\u2019 Gang |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-james-gunn-casts-steve-agee-king-shark-1202703447/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=August 24, 2019 |date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, [[Idris Elba]], [[John Cena]], [[Storm Reid]],<ref name=\"CenaReidJoinCast\"/> [[Flula Borg]],<ref name=\"Borg cast\">{{cite web|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-james-gunn-flula-borg-joins-cast-1202671315/|title='Pitch Perfect 2's Flula Borg Joins James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'|date=August 19, 2019|accessdate=August 19, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref> [[Nathan Fillion]], [[Peter Capaldi]], [[Pete Davidson]], [[Alice Braga]], [[Sean Gunn]], [[Michael Rooker]], [[Taika Waititi]], [[Joaqu\u00edn Cos\u00edo]], Mayling Ng, [[Juan Diego Botto]], Tinashe Kajese, Julio Ruiz, and Jennifer Holland have been cast in undisclosed roles.<ref name=\"Fillion\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-nathan-fillion-rookie-star-joins-cast-james-gunn-movie-1202702610/|title=Nathan Fillion Boarding James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=August 25, 2019|accessdate=August 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Capaldi\">{{cite web|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/suicide-squad-snl-pete-davidson-peter-capaldi-cast-james-gunn-dc-movie-1202709645/|title='Doctor Who's Peter Capaldi Joining James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'; Is 'SNL's Pete Davidson Next?|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=September 3, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref><ref name=\"io9: Cast\">{{cite web |last1=Whitbrook |first1=James |title=Say Hello to the Very Disposable Stars of The Suicide Squad |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/say-hello-to-the-very-disposable-stars-of-the-suicide-s-1838105121 |website=[[io9]] |accessdate=September 13, 2019 |date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Elba was originally cast as [[Deadshot|Floyd Lawton / Deadshot]], replacing [[Will Smith]] from the first film, but [[Warner Bros.]] and director [[James Gunn]] eventually decided to have him play a new character instead, allowing Smith the opportunity to return in a future film.<ref name=\"ElbaRobbie\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:James Gunn (28557194032) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|James Gunn, writer and director of ''The Suicide Squad'']]\n\nIn March 2016, ahead of the release of ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'', [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] announced a sequel was in development. [[David Ayer]] and [[Will Smith]] were respectively attached to reprise their roles as director and [[Deadshot]], and filming was on track to begin in 2017 after the pair completed work on ''[[Bright (film)|Bright]]''.<ref name=\"SequelDevelopingTW\" /><ref name=\"SequelDevelopingV\" /> The following month, Ayer expressed an interest in making the sequel R-rated,<ref name=\"AyerMakingR-rated\" /> but by December had exited in favor of directing ''[[Gotham City Sirens#Film|Gotham City Sirens]]''.<ref name=\"AyerDevelopingGCS\" /> Warner Bros. entered negotiations with [[Mel Gibson]] to direct shortly afterwards,<ref name=\"GibsonTalks\" /> but he passed after production delays.<ref name=\"PennSubmitted\" /> [[Daniel Espinosa]], [[Jonathan Levine]], and [[Ruben Fleischer]] were also under consideration.<ref name=\"GibsonTalks\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Kroll|first=Justin|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/suicide-squad-2-director-mel-gibson-jonathan-levine-ruben-fleischer-1201989606/|title=''Suicide Squad 2'': Mel Gibson, Jonathan Levine, Ruben Fleischer Among Directors Being Considered for Sequel|date=February 15, 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'' writer [[Adam Cozad]] was hired to write the screenplay. The ''Suicide Squad'' sequel was said to be a priority for Warner Bros., with a focus on coming up with a story.<ref name=\"CozadHired\" />\n\nWarner Bros.' top choice to direct was [[Jaume Collet-Serra]], but he passed in favor of [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]'s ''[[Jungle Cruise (film)|Jungle Cruise]]'' because he did not like the idea of continuing a story another director started.<ref name=\"Collet-SerraFrontrunner\" /><ref name=\"Collet-SerraExited\" /> [[David S. Goyer]] was also considered to direct the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|url=https://collider.com/suicide-squad-2-green-lantern-director-david-goyer/|title=Rumor: David Goyer Could Direct ''Suicide Squad 2'' or ''Green Lantern Corps''|date=March 17, 2017|work=Collider|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref>  In July, [[Zak Penn]] pitched a new story treatment and had begun a new draft as a favor for the studio.<ref name=\"PennSubmitted\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Deckelmeir|first=Joe|url=https://screenrant.com/matrix-reboot-zak-penn-shared-universe/|title=Exclusive: Zak Penn Wants To Expand ''The Matrix'' Universe|date=March 13, 2018|work=ScreenRant|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> At [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that month, the film was officially titled ''Suicide Squad 2''.<ref name=\"TitleSDComicCon\" /> By August, [[Jared Leto]] was set to reprise his role as the [[Joker (character)|Joker]] from the first film,<ref name=\"Leto reprise\"/> and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported production would not begin until late 2018 because of Smith's production schedule on ''[[Aladdin (2019 film)|Aladdin]]'' and ''[[Gemini Man (film)|Gemini Man]]''.<ref name=\"KrollTwitter\" /> In September, [[Gavin O'Connor (filmmaker)|Gavin O'Connor]] was hired to direct and co-write the film with ''[[Warrior (2011 film)|Warrior]]'' screenwriter Anthony Tambakis.<ref name=\"ConnorToDirect\" /><ref name=\"ConnorToWrite\" /> [[Michael De Luca]] joined the project as producer alongside [[Charles Roven]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kroll|first=Justin|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/suicide-squad-2-michael-de-luca-1202645015/|title=''Suicide Squad 2'': Michael De Luca Joins Charles Roven on Producer Team|date=January 11, 2018|work=Variety|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> O'Connor brought in [[David Bar Katz]] and [[Todd Stashwick]] to co-write the screenplay in June 2018,<ref name=\"NewWritersJune2018\" /> which was finished in September and featured the Suicide Squad attempting to track down [[Black Adam]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=How 'Suicide Squad 2' May Introduce The Rock's Black Adam (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/suicide-squad-2-the-rock-black-adam-exclusive/ |website=[[TheWrap]] |accessdate=May 2, 2019 |date=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discussingfilm.net/2018/09/15/todd-stashwick-talks-12-monkeys-kim-possible-suicide-squad-2-more-exclusive/|title=Todd Stashwick Talks '12 Monkeys', 'Kim Possible', 'Suicide Squad 2 & More. (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Fisher|first=Jacob|date=September 15, 2018|website=Discussing Film|language=en|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> According to ''Variety''{{'s}} Justin Kroll, O'Connor's script was too similar to the one for ''[[Birds of Prey (2020 film)|Birds of Prey]]'', which Warner Bros. gave a [[green-light|green light]] to first. Frustrated, O'Connor withdrew from the project in favor of ''[[The Way Back (2020 film)|The Way Back]]''.<ref name=\"IGNKroll\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/10/10/birds-of-prey-reportedly-why-suicide-squad-2-lost-its-latest-director|title=Birds of Prey Reportedly Why Suicide Squad 2 Lost Its Latest Director|last=Santangelo|first=Nick|date=October 9, 2018|website=IGN|language=en-US|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMonths earlier, in July 2018, [[The Walt Disney Company]] and [[Marvel Studios]] dismissed [[James Gunn]] from directing the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3]]'' after conservative commentators began circulating old controversial tweets surrounding topics such as rape and pedophilia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/james-gunn-exits-guardians-galaxy-vol-3-1128786|title=James Gunn Fired as Director of 'Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3'|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|last2=Couch|first2=Aaron|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 20, 2018|accessdate=July 20, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/7140aVUQw?url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/james-gunn-exits-guardians-galaxy-vol-3-1128786|archivedate=July 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, Warner Bros. immediately became interested in recruiting him to direct a [[DC Extended Universe]] film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/james-gunn-demand-major-studio-movies-disney-firing-1133161|title=James Gunn in Demand for Major Studio Movies After Disney Firing|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=August 10, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/71YFQU5Kb?url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/james-gunn-demand-major-studio-movies-disney-firing-1133161|archivedate=August 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"DS: Details\"/> and offered him a number of properties, including [[Superman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/report-before-the-suicide-squad-james-gunn-was-offered-superman|title=Report: Before The Suicide Squad, James Gunn was offered Superman|last=Kaye|first=Don|publisher=[[Syfy Wire]]|date=February 4, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76W7DaWPy|archivedate=February 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Gunn chose the ''Suicide Squad'' sequel, and by the time he completed his exit settlement with Disney and Marvel in October, Warner Bros. hired him to write the screenplay and potentially direct.<ref name=\"GunnWriting\" /><ref name=\"GunnHired\" /> Ayer supported the decision, saying that Gunn's hiring was a \"brave and smart move\" by Warner Bros. and calling him \"the right man for the job\",<ref name=\"AyerResponse\" /> while fellow ''Guardians of the Galaxy'' alumnus [[Dave Bautista]] expressed interest in appearing in the film.<ref name=\"IGNKroll\"/>\n\n===Pre-production===\nBy January 2019, Gunn had been hired to direct and Warner Bros. retitled the film ''The Suicide Squad'', with production set to start in September for a scheduled August 6, 2021 release date.<ref name=\"ProductionStart\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/suicide-squad-2-will-smith-not-returning-1202566772/|title=Will Smith Will Not Return As Deadshot In James Gunn's 'Suicide Squad 2'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=February 28, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Couch|first1=Aaron|last2=McClintock|first2=Pamela|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-suicide-squad-sequel-set-2021-release-dates-1181432|title='The Batman,' 'The Suicide Squad' Set 2021 Release Dates|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> [[Charles Roven]] and [[Peter Safran]] were also attached to produce.<ref name=\"DeadlineRelease\"/> Safran stated the film was retitled \"because it's a total reboot ... It's everything you would hope from a James Gunn script and I think that says a lot and that promises a lot and I know that we will deliver a lot.\"<ref name=\"DS: Details\">{{cite web |last1=Armitage |first1=Hugh |last2=Chapman |first2=Matt |last3=Ashurst |first3=Sam |title=Suicide Squad 2 cast, release date, plot and everything you need to know |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a837989/suicide-squad-2-cast-trailer-release-date-plot-news/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=September 23, 2019 |date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> Although Disney had reinstated Gunn as director of ''Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3'' by March, production for that film would not begin until he completed his work on ''The Suicide Squad''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/james-gunn-reinstated-guardians-of-the-galaxy-3-disney-suicide-squad-2-indefensible-social-media-messages-1202576444/|title=Disney Reinstates Director James Gunn For \u2018Guardians Of The Galaxy 3\u2019|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 15, 2019|accessdate=March 15, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76thA7oq6|archivedate=March 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' confirmed Smith would not be reprising his role as Deadshot from the first film due to scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Couch |first1=Aaron |title=Will Smith Not Returning for 'Suicide Squad' Sequel |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-2-loses-will-smith-1191348 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=May 3, 2019 |date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> Gunn met with [[Idris Elba]] to discuss replacing him, which \"went so swimmingly that talks began with the studio in earnest.\" Elba, who was the only choice of Gunn and Warner Bros., signed on to portray Deadshot in March.<ref name=\"ElbaTHR\">{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Idris Elba in Talks to Replace Will Smith in 'Suicide Squad' Sequel (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/idris-elba-replacing-will-smith-suicide-squad-sequel-1191349 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 6, 2019 |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> However, by April Gunn and Warner Bros. had decided to have Elba portray a different character, which would enable Smith to return in a future film.<ref name=\"ElbaRobbie\">{{cite news |last1=Kroll |first1=Justin |title=\u2018The Suicide Squad\u2019: Deadshot Removed from Sequel as Idris Elba Moves to New Character (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/suicide-squad-sequel-idris-elba-new-character-1203181518/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=April 5, 2019 |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> At that time, [[Viola Davis]] and [[Margot Robbie]] had been confirmed to return as [[Amanda Waller]] and [[Harley Quinn]],<ref name=\"ElbaRobbie\" /><ref name=\"Davis\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=Viola Davis to Return as Amanda Waller in James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/viola-davis-amanda-waller-the-suicide-squad/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> while [[Jai Courtney]] announced he would be reprising his role as [[Captain Boomerang]] in an interview.<ref name=\"Courtney\">{{cite news |last1=Guerrasio |first1=Jason |title=Jai Courtney says he will be back playing Captain Boomerang in the James Gunn 'Suicide Squad' movie |url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/jai-courtney-is-captain-boomerang-in-james-gunn-suicide-squad-movie-2019-3 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |work=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The involvement of [[Joel Kinnaman]], who portrayed [[Rick Flag]] in the first film, was initially unclear,<ref name=\"ElbaTHR\"/> but he was set to return by July.<ref name=\"CenaReidJoinCast\"/> Leto's involvement was also unclear,<ref name=\"DS: Details\"/> and unlike Kinnaman he was not expected to appear by September.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carbone |first1=Gina |title=No Jared Leto In The Suicide Squad Cast? DC Fans Have Strong Feelings About That |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2480285/no-jared-leto-in-the-suicide-squad-cast-dc-fans-have-strong-feelings-about-that |website=CinemaBlend |accessdate=September 23, 2019 |date=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt this point, production of ''The Suicide Squad'' was set to begin after Robbie finished her work on ''Birds of Prey''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harp |first1=Justin |title=James Gunn's Suicide Squad is bringing back the best character from the original amid Idris Elba shake-up |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a27060021/suicide-squad-james-gunn-viola-davis-idris-elba-not-deadshot/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=May 3, 2019 |date=April 6, 2019}}</ref> ''The Suicide Squad'' was described as a new take on the property rather than a direct sequel to the 2016 film.<ref name=\"Dastmalchian\" /> Unlike Ayer, who was primarily inspired by the [[New 52]] Suicide Squad comics, Gunn drew inspiration from the 1980s comics by [[John Ostrander]] and [[Kim Yale]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Sam |title=REPORT: James Gunn's Suicide Squad Will Draw From This Iconic Run |url=https://www.cbr.com/james-gunns-suicide-squad-draw-john-ostrander-kim-yale/ |website=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=May 3, 2019 |date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> As such, Gunn decided to focus more on characters who were not introduced in ''Suicide Squad'', such as a female version of the [[Ratcatcher (comics)|Ratcatcher]], [[Polka-Dot Man]], [[King Shark]], and [[Peacemaker (comics)|Peacemaker]].<ref name=\"Dastmalchian\" /><ref name=\"ColliderCharacters\"/> Gunn was said to be considering casting Bautista as Peacemaker,<ref name=\"ColliderCharacters\">{{cite web |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |title='Suicide Squad 2' Exclusive: Meet the New Characters James Gunn Will Introduce in Sequel |url=https://collider.com/suicide-squad-2-new-characters/#images |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=May 3, 2019 |date=March 7, 2019}}</ref> though this could not happen due to scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"IGNCena\">{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=Colin |title=John Cena in Talks to Join Suicide Squad 2, Margot Robbie Returns as Harley Quinn |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/04/17/john-cena-in-talks-to-join-suicide-squad-sequel-margot-robbie-returns-as-harley-quinn |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=May 3, 2019 |date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> In April, [[David Dastmalchian]] and [[Daniela Melchior]] were cast as Polka-Dot Man and Ratcatcher, respectively.<ref name=\"Dastmalchian\" /><ref name=\"Melchior cast\" /> [[John Cena]] entered talks for an unspecified role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/john-cena-eyed-suicide-squad-sequel-role-1202693|title=John Cena Eyed for Role in 'Suicide Squad' Sequel|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|language=en|access-date=April 18, 2019|date=April 17, 2019|last=Galuppo|first=Mia}}</ref> In July, [[Storm Reid]] joined the cast, while Cena's involvement was confirmed.<ref name=\"CenaReidJoinCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/storm-reid-joins-james-gunns-suicide-squad-1223553|title=Storm Reid Joins Idris Elba in James Gunn's 'The Suicide Squad'|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 10, 2019|accessdate=July 12, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> In August, [[Flula Borg]] and [[Nathan Fillion]] were cast in an undisclosed roles,<ref name=\"Borg cast\" /><ref name=\"Fillion\" /> and [[Steve Agee]] was hired to voice King Shark,<ref name=\"Agee cast\" /> with [[Taika Waititi]] entering negotiations to join in an unspecified role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/suicide-squad-taika-waititi-in-talks-to-star-james-gunn-dc-film-cast-1202704115/|title=Taika Waititi In Talks For Role In James Gunn\u2019s \u2018Suicide Squad\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref> In September, [[Peter Capaldi]] joined the cast, and [[Pete Davidson]] entered negotiations for a [[Cameo appearance|cameo]].<ref name=\"Capaldi\" /> The remainder of the cast was confirmed later in the month.<ref name=\"io9: Cast\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on September 20, 2019, at [[Pinewood Atlanta Studios]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=\"Capaldi\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Schmidt |first1=J.K. |title=James Gunn Reveals The Suicide Squad Begins Filming |url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/09/20/james-gunn-reveals-the-suicide-squad-begins-filming/ |website=ComicBook.com |accessdate=September 22, 2019 |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> Filming in Atlanta was expected to last three months before transitioning to [[Panama]] for a month.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis|first=Brandon|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/09/13/the-suicide-squad-filming-atlanta-panama-production-release-date/|title=James Gunn's The Suicide Squad to Begin Filming in Atlanta, Head to Panama|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=September 14, 2019|website=ComicBook.com}}</ref> [[Joel Kinnaman]] described the film as a [[comedy film|comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/podcasts/joel-kinnaman-for-all-mankind-suicide-squad-sequel-1203382082/|title=Joel Kinnaman Talks Apple\u2019s \u2018For All Mankind,\u2019 \u2018Suicide Squad\u2019 Sequel|website=Variety|last=Malkin|first=Marc|date=October 24, 2019|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Filming wrapped on February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/the-suicide-squad-james-gunn-wraps-filming/|title=James Gunn announces shooting has wrapped on The Suicide Squad|last=Collis|first=Clark|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nJames Gunn confirmed that he is currently editing the movie at his home and that the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|COVID-19]] Pandemic didn't affect the movie's post-production and release date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/guardians-of-the-galaxy-3-suicide-squad-sequel-james-gunn-release-date-1234578230/|title=\u2018Guardians of the Galaxy 3,\u2019 \u2018The Suicide Squad\u2019 Won\u2019t Be Delayed, Says James Gunn|last=Moreau|first=Jordan|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412223324/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/guardians-of-the-galaxy-3-suicide-squad-sequel-james-gunn-release-date-1234578230/|archivedate=April 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Suicide Squad'' is scheduled for release by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] in the United States on August 6, 2021.<ref name=\"DeadlineRelease\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/warner-bros-release-dates-galore-doctor-sleep-checks-in-this-november-the-witches-oct-2020-the-suicide-squad-returns-in-2021-1202546092/|title=Warner Bros. Release Dates Galore: 'Doctor Sleep' Checks In This November, 'The Witches' Oct. 2020; 'The Suicide Squad' Returns In 2021|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=SequelDevelopingTW>{{cite web | url=https://www.thewrap.com/will-smith-joel-edgerton-to-star-in-david-ayers-cop-thriller-bright/ | title=Will Smith, Joel Edgerton to Star in David Ayer's Cop Thriller 'Bright' | work=[[TheWrap]] | date=March 2, 2016 | accessdate=March 3, 2016 | last=Snider | first=Jeff | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305122926/http://www.thewrap.com/will-smith-joel-edgerton-to-star-in-david-ayers-cop-thriller-bright/# | archive-date=March 5, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SequelDevelopingV>{{cite web | date=March 2, 2016 | first1=Justin | last1=Kroll | url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/will-smith-david-ayer-bright-suicide-squad-1201696226/ | title=Will Smith, David Ayer Reteaming on Max Landis Spec 'Bright' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | accessdate=