| last = Strohm\n  | first = Paul\n  | editor1-last= Harris\n  | editor1-first= Stephen J.\n  | editor2-last= Grigsby\n  | editor2-first= Bryon Lee\n  | year = 2008\n  | chapter = A 'Peasants' Revolt'?\n  | title = Misconceptions About the Middle Ages\n  | edition =\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | location= New York\n  | isbn = 978-0-415-77053-8\n  | pages = 197\u2013203\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Sumption\n  | first = Jonathan\n  | year = 2009\n  | title = Divided Houses: the Hundred Years War III\n  | publisher = Faber and Faber\n  | location= London\n  | isbn = 978-0-571-24012-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Trevelyan\n  | first = George\n  | year = 1899\n  | title = England in the Age of Wycliffe\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/englandinageofwy01trev\n  | publisher = Longmans and Green\n  | location= London| oclc = 12771030\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tuck\n  | first = J. A.\n  | editor1-last=Hilton\n  | editor1-first=Rodney\n  | editor2-last=Alton\n  | editor2-first=T. H.\n  | year = 1987\n  | chapter = Nobles, Commons and the Great Revolt of 1381\n  | title = The English Rising of 1381\n  | edition =\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | location= Cambridge| isbn = 978-1-84383-738-1\n  | pages = 192\u2013212\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n |last=Wickert\n |first=Maria\n |date=2016\n |title=Studies in John Gower\n |orig-year=1953\n |location=Tempe, Arizona\n |publisher=Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies\n |page=18\n |isbn=9780866985413\n |ref=harv\n |translator-last=Meindl\n |translator-first=Robert J. }}{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ancient.eu/Peasants'_Revolt/ The Peasants' Revolt - Ancient History Encyclopedia]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0038x8s The Peasants' Revolt], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Miri Rubin, Caroline Barron & Alastair Dunn (''In Our Time'', Nov. 16, 2006)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4kq9sbtFCR8], The Peasants' Revolt Of 1381 presented by Tony Robinson.\n*{{Commons category-inline|English Peasants' Revolt}}\n\n{{Riots in England}}\n{{London history}}\n{{Tax resistance}}\n{{Medieval and Early Modern European Peasant Wars}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:14th century in London]]\n[[Category:Peasants' Revolt| ]]\n[[Category:History of Essex]]\n[[Category:History of Kent]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Battles and military actions in London]]\n[[Category:Protests in England]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in medieval England]]\n[[Category:Richard II of England]]\n[[Category:1381 in England]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1381]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:70f5:700:c993:48c2:a345:9e52", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added info)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peasants%27_Revolt"}
{"title_page": "Al-Zarrar tank", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{infobox weapon\n| name               =Al-Zarrar \n| image              =File:Alzarrar.jpg \n| caption            =Al-Zarrar [[Main battle tank|MBT]] during the [[International Defence Exhibition and Seminar|IDEAS Convention]] in [[Karachi Expo Center]], [[Circa|ca.]] [[2008 in Pakistan|2008]].\n| type               =[[Main battle tank]] \n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_vehicle         =Yes \n| service            =[[2004 in Pakistan|2004]]\u2013Present\n| wars               =[[War in North-West Pakistan]]<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           =[[Heavy Industries Taxila]] \n| number             =504 <ref name=\"MF\"/> \n| spec_label         = \n| length             = {{convert|31.17|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n| width              = {{convert|10.83|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n| height             = {{convert|8.20|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n| diameter           = \n| passengers         =\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications --> \n| action             = \n| sheath_type        = \n| head_type          = \n| haft_type          = \n<!-- Explosive specifications --> \n| image_size         =260px\n| alt                =\n| origin             = Pakistan/China\n| is_ranged          =No \n| is_bladed          =No \n| is_explosive       =No \n| is_artillery       =No \n| is_missile         =No \n| is_UK              =No\n<!-- Service history -->\n| used_by            = [[Pakistan Army]]\n| design_date        =1990s \n| manufacturer       =Heavy Industries Taxila \n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    =6 May 2003 \n| variants           =''None''\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| weight             = {{convert|44|t|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MF\">{{cite web|title=HIT Al-Zarrar Main Battle Tank|url=http://www.militaryfactory.com/armor/detail.asp?armor_id=605|website=www.militaryfactory.com/|publisher=MF|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n| part_length        = \n| crew               ='''4'''<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n| cartridge          =125mm smoothbore \n| cartridge_weight   = \n| caliber            =125 mm<ref name=\"MF\"/> \n| barrels            = \n| rate               = \n| velocity           =\n| range              = \n| max_range          = \n| feed               = \n| sights             = \n<!-- Artillery specifications -->\n| breech             = \n| recoil             = \n| carriage           = \n| elevation          = \n| traverse           = \n<!-- Bladed weapon specifications --> \n| blade_type         = \n| hilt_type          = \n| filling            = \n| filling_weight     = \n| detonation         = \n| yield              = \n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| armour             =Modular [[composite armour]]<br />[[Reactive armour|Explosive reactive armour]]<ref name=\"Army Technology\">{{cite web|title=Al-Zarrar Main Battle Tank (MBT)|url=http://www.army-technology.com/projects/alzarrarmianbattleta/|website=Army Technology|publisher=Army Technology|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n| primary_armament   =[[125 mm smoothbore ammunition|125mm smoothbore ammunition]]<ref name=\"Army Technology\"/>\n| secondary_armament =[[12.7mm NATO|12.7 mm]] external anti-aircraft machine gun<ref name=\"Army Technology\"/><br />[[7.62 mm]] [[coaxial]] machine gun<br>8x smoke grade dischargers \n| engine             =1x[[Kharkiv Morozov Machine Building Design Bureau|KMDB]] [[12-cylinder engine|12 cylinder]] [[Liquid-cooled engine|liquid cooled]] [[Diesel engine|diesel]]<ref name=\"Army Technology\"/> \n| engine_power       =730 [[Horsepower|hp]]<ref name=\"Army Technology\"/>\n| pw_ratio           =18.3 hp/tonne<ref name=\"Army Technology\"/> \n| payload_capacity   = \n| transmission       = \n| suspension         =[[Torsion bar suspension|High-hardness-steel torsion bar]]<ref name=\"MF\"/> \n| clearance          = \n| fuel_capacity      = \n| vehicle_range      = {{convert|450|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MF\"/> \n| speed              = {{convert|65|km|abbr=on}}/h<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n| guidance           = \n| steering           = \n<!-- Missiles only -->\n| wingspan           = \n| propellant         = \n| ceiling            = \n| altitude           = \n| depth              = \n| boost              = \n| accuracy           = \n| launch_platform    = \n| transport          =\n}}\n{{T-54/55 navigation}}\n{{Post-Cold War tanks}}\nThe '''Al-Zarrar''' ([[Urdu]]: \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0631\u0627\u0631), is a [[List of main battle tanks by generation#Third  generation|third generation]] [[main battle tank]] (MBT), currently in the services of the [[Pakistan Army]] since 2004. The tank is named after Muslim warrior [[Dhiraar bin Al-Azwar|Zarrar bin Al-Azwar]].<ref name=\"Dawn Newspapers, 2003\">{{cite news |title=50 Al Zarrar tanks to be exported this year|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/77650|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=Dawn |publisher=Dawn Newspapers |date=15 January 2003|location=Islamabad|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defence.pk/pdf/threads/zarrar-bin-azwar-the-naked-warrior.313906/|title=Zarrar bin Azwar - The Naked warrior|website=Pakistan Defence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIt is an upgrade of Pakistan's aging Chinese [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] tanks (a design that in turn was based on the Soviet [[T-54A]] from the mid 1950s), developed with Ukrainian assistance<ref name=\"MF\"/> and manufactured by the [[Heavy Industries Taxila| Heavy Industries Taxila (HIT)]], featuring a 125&nbsp;mm smoothbore gun as primary weapon. The Al-Zarrar can achieve a maximum speed of {{convert|65|km|abbr=on}} per hour, weighs around 44 tons and has a four-man crew: commander, gunner, loader and driver.<ref name=\"MF\" /><ref name=\"Bangladesh Defence\">{{cite web|title=Bangladesh Army is going to upgrade Type 59 Tanks|url=http://www.defencebd.com/2014/06/bangladesh-army-is-going-to-upgrade.html|website=Bangladesh Defence|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the upgrade program started in 1990 the Al-Zarrar did not enter military service with the [[Pakistan Army Armoured Corps]] until 2004, gradually replacing the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59s]]. Attempts were made to export the Al-Zarrar to the [[Bangladeshi Army]] in 2008 to replace its fleet of [[Type 59 tank|Type 59G]] through the [[technology transfer]]. However, no progress was made through this deal and as of 2017, Pakistan Army remained its sole operator.<ref name=\"Gordon Arthur, Defence Review\">{{cite web|last1=Arthur|first1=Gordon|title=Main Battle Tanks in Asia|url=http://www.defencereviewasia.com/articles/204/MAIN-BATTLE-TANKS-IN-ASIA|website=www.defencereviewasia.com|publisher=Gordon Arthur, Defence Review|accessdate=7 June 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710154921/http://www.defencereviewasia.com/articles/204/MAIN-BATTLE-TANKS-IN-ASIA|archive-date=10 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIt was decided by the [[Pakistan Army]] that their inventory of Chinese origin [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] tanks was too large to be discarded and replaced, so a phased upgrade programme was started by [[Heavy Industries Taxila|Heavy Industries Taxila (HIT)]] in 1990. The idea was to upgrade the firepower, mobility and protection of the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] to allow it to compete on the modern battlefield at a fraction of the cost of a modern [[main battle tank|main battle tank (MBT)]]. The first phase of the upgrade programme was completed in 1997. The second phase started in 1998 when HIT began development and testing of a new tank, a [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] re-built with over 50 modifications, resulting in three prototypes with slightly differing specifications (different fire-control systems, for example). Many systems originally developed for HIT's [[Al-Khalid]] MBT were incorporated. The prototypes underwent extensive testing by HIT and the [[Pakistan Army]], who selected the final version of the tank, dubbed Al-Zarrar.\n\nBy mid 2004, it was expected that 50 AL-Zarrar tanks would be exported to other countries.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Al Zarrar tanks to be exported this year|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/77650/50-al-zarrar-tanks-to-be-exported-this-year|accessdate=31 July 2015|work=Dawn|date=15 January 2003}}</ref>\nThe '''Al-Zarrar''' is a modern [[main battle tank]] (MBT) developed and manufactured by [[Heavy Industries Taxila|Heavy Industries Taxila (HIT)]] of [[Pakistan]] for the [[Pakistan Army]]. \nAn upgraded variant of the Chinese [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] tank, the Al-Zarrar is cost-effective modern replacement for the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] fleet of the [[Pakistan Army]]. Equipped with modern [[armament]], [[Fire-control system|fire control]] and ballistic protection, the Al-Zarrar upgrade is also offered by [[Heavy Industries Taxila|HIT]] to the armies of foreign countries to upgrade their [[T-54]]/[[T-55]] or [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] tanks to Al-Zarrar standard. 54 modifications made to the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] make the Al-Zarrar effectively a new tank.\n\nThe Al-Zarrar development programme started in 1990. HIT began mass production of Al-Zarrar on 6 May 2003 under a renowned Project Manager, Engineer Mahmood Khan. First batch of 88 Al-Zarrar were delivered to the Pakistan Army on 26 February 2004. Delivery ceremony was graced by General Pervez Musharraf.\n\n==Design==\n[[Image:alzarar.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Al-Zarrar MBTs of the [[Pakistan Army]]'s 27th Cavalry regiment stationed at [[Kharian]].]]\n[[Image:alzarar27cav.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Al-Zarrar MBTs of the [[Pakistan Army]]'s 27th Cavalry regiment stationed at [[Kharian]].]]\n\n===Armament and fire-control===\nAl-Zarrar's primary armament is a 125&nbsp;mm [[smoothbore]] [[tank gun]] with an [[autofrettage]]d, chrome-plated gun barrel. It is capable of firing [[APFSDS]], [[HEAT]]-FS and [[High Explosive|HE]]-FS rounds as well as [[anti-tank guided missile]]s and a Pakistani [[depleted uranium|DU (depleted uranium)]] round, the 125&nbsp;mm Naiza. Naiza is capable of penetrating 550&nbsp;mm of RHA armour at a distance of 2&nbsp;km. Reloaded by a semi-automatic [[autoloader]], the gun has a dual-axis stabilization system and thermal imaging sights integrated into the fire-control system for the commander and gunner. The image stabilized fire-control system includes a [[laser range-finder]] for accurate range information and ballistics computer to improve accuracy.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} An improved gun control system is also fitted.\n\nThe secondary armament consists of an external 12.7&nbsp;mm anti-aircraft machine gun mounted on the roof of the turret, which can be aimed and fired from inside the tank, and a 7.62&nbsp;mm [[Coaxial weapon|coaxial]] machine gun.\n\n===Mobility===\nThe Al-Zarrar  is powered by a liquid-cooled 12-cylinder [[diesel engine]], giving a power output of {{convert|730|hp|abbr=on}} and torque output of 305&nbsp;kg.m at 1300\u20131400&nbsp;rpm. A combat weight of 40 tonnes gives Al-Zarrar a [[power-to-weight ratio]] of 18.3&nbsp;hp/tonne and a top speed of 65&nbsp;km/h. \nCrew comfort is improved over the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] by a modified [[torsion bar]] suspension system.\n\n===Protection===\nAl-Zarrar uses modular composite armour and [[explosive reactive armour]] to give improved protection from anti-tank missiles, mines and other weapons. \nThe Pakistani ATCOP LTS-1 laser threat warning system is fitted to inform the tank crew if the tank is targeted by a [[laser range-finder]] or [[laser designator]]. Smoke grenade launchers are fitted to the sides of the turret. An automatic fire-extinguishing and explosion suppression system is installed to improve crew survivability.\n\n==Operators==\n===Current operators===\n;{{PAK}}\n* [[Pakistan Army]]: 504 in service with the [[Pakistan Army]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=28466:pakistan-and-china-to-jointly-market-al-khalid-tank&catid=112:ideas-2012&Itemid=249|title=Pakistan and China to jointly market Al Khalid tank}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armyrecognition.com/pakistan_pakistani_army_land_ground_forces_uk/pakistan_pakistani_army_land_ground_forces_military_equipment_armoured_armored_vehicle_uk.html|title=Pakistan Land Forces military equipment and vehicles Of Pakistani Army}}</ref>\n===Failed bids===\n;{{BAN}}\nIn October 2008, the chief of the [[Bangladesh Army]] met his [[Pakistan Army|Pakistani]] counterpart to discuss a programme to modernise [[Bangladesh]]'s fleet of [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]] tanks.<ref name=\"bdmilitary.com\">[http://www.bdmilitary.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=271&Itemid=97 Al Zarrar Main Battle Tank | Bangladesh Military Forces | BDMilitary.com - The voice of the Bangladesh Armed Forces<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan, BD army chiefs discuss defence co-operation |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008%5C10%5C22%5Cstory_22-10-2008_pg7_22 |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |newspaper=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)]] |date=October 22, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A joint venture  was formed with Pakistan to upgrade the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59/59II]] tanks to Al-Zarrar MBT standard. Pakistan will transfer the relevant technology to Bangladesh under the joint venture. About 300 tanks are expected to be modernized under the project, which will be carried out in Bangladesh at the Bangladesh Army's 902 Heavy Workshop.<ref name=armytech>{{cite web|title=Al-Zarrar Main Battle Tank (MBT), Pakistan|url=http://www.army-technology.com/projects/alzarrarmianbattleta/|work=army-technology.com|accessdate=28 June 2013}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\nNo progress on the deal was reported as of 2015.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Main battle tank]]\n* [[Pakistan Army]]\n;Related development\n* [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]]\n;Comparable tanks\n* [[Ramses II Main Battle Tank|Ramses II]]\n* [[Type 59G(BD) Durjoy]]\n* [[Sabra (tank)]]\n;Related Lists\n* [[List of armoured fighting vehicles]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Al-Zarrar tanks}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090724174938/http://usmanansari.com/id15.html Heavy Metal - Pakistani AFVs, by Usman Ansari]* [http://www.bdmilitary.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=271 Al-Zarrar Main Battle Tank at Bangladesh Military Forces website]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2004/02/mil-040226-irna03.htm GlobalSecurity.org - Pakistan Army gets first consignment of 80 Chinese-origin tanks]\n;Pictures of Al-Zarrar in service during anti-insurgency operations\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_pictures/8038258.stm Al-Zarrar in service in [[Swat, Pakistan]].]\n* [http://english.aljazeera.net/mritems/Images/2009/5/7/200957165740715734_2.jpg An Al-Zarrar believed to have been destroyed during anti-insurgency operations in [[Swat, Pakistan]].]\n\n{{Tanks of Pakistan |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Military of Pakistan}}\n\n[[Category:Main battle tanks of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Main battle tanks of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War main battle tanks]]\n[[Category:Tanks of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:China\u2013Pakistan military relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{infobox weapon\n| name               =Al-Zarrar \n| image              =File:Alzarrar.jpg \n| caption            =Al-Zarrar [[Main battle tank|MBT]] during the [[International Defence Exhibition and Seminar|IDEAS Convention]] in [[Karachi Expo Center]], [[Circa|ca.]] [[2008 in Pakistan|2008]].\n| type               =[[Main battle tank]] \n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_vehicle         =Yes \n| service            =[[2004 in Pakistan|2004]]\u2013Present\n| wars               =[[War in North-West Pakistan]]<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           =[[Heavy Industri